<section xml:id="section-activity-clo7">
  <title>Activity for CLO-7</title>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-clo7-review">
    <title>Conceptual Review</title>
    <p>
      You can test your learning from the video (and your own
      background knowledge) with the following review questions.
      Conceptual questions on quizes may be taken from these review
      questions. 
    </p>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is an autonomous differential equation. Why is it a
          useful definition?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It is a differential equation where the derivative is
          isolated on the left and the expression on the right side
          only involves the dependent variable (the function). It is
          useful for two reasons. First, it allows for phase line
          analysis, which is a powerful technique. Second, it shows
          that the dynamics of the system are consistent, not changing
          over time. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is a phase line?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          It is a diagram that qualitively shows the growth dynamics
          of an autonomous differential equation. The diagram is a 
          line, and points on the line are potential starting values
          for the function. Steady states are labelled as dot; if the
          function starts at these values, then it is static. Steady
          means that it doesn't change. Between the steady states, an
          arrow is drawn. This arrow is called the trajectory and it
          shows the growth behaviour. Upward arrows indicate growth
          and downward arrow indicate decay. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          What is logistic growth?
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          Logistic growth is a growth model that acts like exponential
          growth for small value but slows approaching a certain
          value, called the carrying capacity. Similarly, if the
          population start above the carrying capacity, it start out
          like exponential decay but then slows as it approach the
          carrying capacity.
        </p>
        <p>
          Logistic growth represents growth within a limited
          environment. Once all the space or resources are used, the
          population stabilized at a certain value, called the
          carrying capacity. If the population is above the carrying
          capacity, it will shrink back down to that value. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          How is the Malthusian model adjusted to make the logistic
          model>
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          If it adjusted by multiplying by a new term, <m>\left( 1 -
          \frac{p}{K} \right)</m>. Using phase lines, this introduces
          a steady state, which is the carrying capacity, and testing
          on either side of the steady state shows the behaviour of
          approaching the carrying capacity from either side. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-activity-phase-lines">
    <title>Calculation Questions: Phase Lines</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Draw a phase line for this differential equation.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = p^2 - 9p + 18
          </md>
          Determine the steady states and trajectories, then classify
          the steady states. You may assume this is a population
          model, so that <m>p \geq 0</m> and 0 is always a steady
          state.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="figure-phase-line-activity-1">
          <caption>Phase Line for <m>p^2 - 9p + 18</m></caption>
          <image xml:id="figure73" width="100%">
            <asymptote>
              size(16cm,0,IgnoreAspect);

              dot("$0$",(0,0),N);
              dot("$3$",(2,0),N);
              dot("$6$",(4,0),N);
              dot("$\infty$",(6,0),N);

              draw((0,0)--(2,0),MidArrow);
              draw((4,0)--(2,0),MidArrow);
              draw((4,0)--(6,0),MidArrow);
            </asymptote>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          To calculate the phase line, I need the zeros of the right
          side of the equation. This is a quadratic and it factors as
          <m>(p-6)(p-3)</m>. Therefore, there are steady states at
          <m>p=3</m> and <m>p=6</m>. I label these points on the phase
          line. To determine the trajectories, I check the value of
          the right side of the equation between the steady states. 
        </p>
        <p><ul>
          <li>
            At <m>p=1</m>, the right side evaluates to 10, which is
            positive. The trajectory between 0 and 3 is upward. 
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=4</m>, the right side evaluates to -2, which is
            negative. The trajectory between 3 and 6 is downward. 
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=7</m>, the right side evaluates to 4, which is
            positive. The trajectory above 6 is upward. 
          </li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>
          This lets me classify the steady states. 
        </p>
        <p><ul>
          <li>
            The (imposed) steady state at 0 only has an trajectory
            pointing away, so this is an unstable steady state. 
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 3 has trajectories pointing toward it,
            so it is a stable steady state.
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 6 has trajectories pointing away from
            it, so it is an unstable steady state. 
          </li>
        </ul></p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Draw a phase line for the differential equation
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = p^3 - 6p^2 + 11p - 6 
          </md>
          Determine the steady states and trajectories, then classify
          the steady states. You may assume this is a population
          model, so that <m>p \geq 0</m> and 0 is always a steady
          state.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="figure-phase-line-activity-2">
          <caption>Phase Line for <m>p^3 - 6p^2 + 11p - 6</m></caption>
          <image xml:id="figure74" width="100%">
            <asymptote>
              size(16cm,0,IgnoreAspect);

              dot("$0$",(0,0),N);
              dot("$1$",(2,0),N);
              dot("$2$",(4,0),N);
              dot("$3$",(6,0),N);

              dot("$\infty$",(8,0),N);

              draw((2,0)--(0,0),MidArrow);
              draw((2,0)--(4,0),MidArrow);
              draw((6,0)--(4,0),MidArrow);
              draw((6,0)--(8,0),MidArrow);
            </asymptote>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          To calculate the phase line, I need the zeros of the right
          side of the equation. This is a cubic: I can try to look for
          the roots by inspection or ask a computer for the roots. In
          any case, I find that <m>p=1</m>, <m>p=2</m> and <m>p=3</m>
          are the roots. I label these points on the phase line. To
          determine the trajectories, I check the value of the right
          side of the equation between the steady states.
        </p>
        <p><ul>
          <li>
            At <m>p=\frac{1}{2}</m>, the right side evaluates to
            <m>\frac{-15}{8}</m>, which is negative. The trajectory
            between 0 and 1 is downward.
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=\frac{3}{2}</m>, the right side evaluates to
            <m>\frac{3}{8}</m>, which is positive. The trajectory
            between 1 and 2 is upward. 
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=\frac{5}{2}</m>, the right side evaluates to
            <m>\frac{-3}{8}</m>, which is negative. The trajectory
            between 2 and 3 is downward.
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=4</m>, the right side evaluates to 6,
            which is positive. The trajectory above 4 is upward. 
          </li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>
          This lets me classify the steady states. 
        </p>
        <p><ul>
          <li>
            The (imposed) steady state at 0 only has an trajectory
            pointing towards, so this is a stable steady state. 
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 1 has trajectories pointing away from
            it, so it is an unstable steady state. 
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 2 has trajectories pointing toward it,
            so it is a stable steady state.
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 3 has trajectories pointing away from
            it, so it is an unstable steady state. 
          </li>
        </ul></p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Draw a phase line for the differential equation
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = p^3 - 10p^2 + 32 p - 32 
          </md>
          Determine the steady states and trajectories, then classify
          the steady states. You may assume this is a population
          model, so that <m>p \geq 0</m> and 0 is always a steady
          state.
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <figure xml:id="figure-phase-line-activity-3">
          <caption>
            Phase Line for <m>p^3 - 10p^2 + 32p - 32</m>
          </caption>
          <image xml:id="figure75" width="100%">
            <asymptote>
              size(16cm,0,IgnoreAspect);

              dot("$0$",(0,0),N);
              dot("$2$",(2,0),N);
              dot("$4$",(4,0),N);
              dot("$\infty$",(6,0),N);

              draw((2,0)--(0,0),MidArrow);
              draw((2,0)--(4,0),MidArrow);
              draw((4,0)--(6,0),MidArrow);
            </asymptote>
          </image>
        </figure>
        <p>
          To calculate the phase line, I need the zeros of the right
          side of the equation. This is a cubic; I can find the factors
          by inspection or by asking a computer. The roots are
          <m>p=2</m> and <m>p=4</m>. I label these points on the phase
          line. To determine the trajectories, I check the value of the
          right side of the equation between the steady states. 
        </p>
        <p><ul>
          <li>
            At <m>p=1</m>, the right side evaluates to -9, which is
            negative. The trajectory between 0 and 2 is downward. 
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=3</m>, the right side evaluates to 1, which is
            positive. The trajectory between 2 and 4 is upward. 
          </li>
          <li>
            At <m>p=5</m>, the right side evaluates to 5, which is
            positive. The trajectory above 4 is upward. 
          </li>
        </ul></p>
        <p>
          This lets me classify the steady states. 
        </p>
        <p><ul>
          <li>
            The (imposed) steady state at 0 only has an trajectory
            pointing towards, so this is a stable steady state. 
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 2 has trajectories pointing away from
            it, so it is an unstable steady state.
          </li>
          <li>
            The steady state at 4 has one trajectory pointing towards
            and one pointing away. This is neither stable or
            unstable; we can call it partially stable. If I want to
            be more specific, I can say that it is stable from below
            and unstable from above.
          </li>
        </ul></p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
  <subsection xml:id="subsection-calculation-logistic">
    <title>Calculate Questions: Logistic Growth</title>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        Write the logistic model with a natural growth rate of
        <m>3\%</m> and a carrying capacity of <m>1300</m>. 
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can place both constants into the from of the logistic
          model. 
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{3}{100} p \left( 1 - \frac{p}{1300}
            \right) 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        Write the logistic model with a natural growth rate of
        <m>75\%</m> and a carrying capacity of five million.
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          I can place both constants into the from of the logistic
          model. 
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{3}{4} p \left( 1 - \frac{p}{5000000}
            \right) 
          </md>
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
    <activity>
      <statement>
        <p>
          Consider this logistic equation.
          <md>
            \frac{dp}{dt} = \frac{2}{100} p \left( 1 - \frac{p}{757}
            \right) 
          </md>
          What is the natural growth rate and the carrying capacity for
          this equation?
        </p>
        <p>
          Use a computer to calculate the value of the side for a
          sequence of population values which are getting closer and
          closer to the carrying capacity. (Start at 700 and then
          increase in jumps to get closer to the carrying capacity.
          Make at least ten calculations) What do you observe about
          the growth rate as the population gets closer and closer to
          the carrying capacity? (Decimal approxmiations are
          appropriate for this question). 
        </p>
      </statement>
      <solution>
        <p>
          The natural growth rate is <m>2\%</m> and the carrying
          capacity is <m>757</m>. 
        </p>
        <p>
          here is a table of value for the right side for various
          numbers starting at 700. I'll increase by 5 at the start,
          and then increase by 1 once I reach 750.
          <tabular>
            <row top="minor" bottom="minor">
              <cell>
                Population
              </cell>
              <cell>
                Growth Rate
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                700
              </cell>
              <cell>
                1.054
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                700
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.882
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                720
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.704
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                730
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.521
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                740
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.332
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                750
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.139
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                751
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.119
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                752
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.0993
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                753
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.0796
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                754
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.0560
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                755
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.0399
              </cell>
            </row>
            <row>
              <cell>
                756
              </cell>
              <cell>
                0.0200
              </cell>
            </row>
          </tabular>
        </p>
        <p>
          I notice the decreasing growth rate approaching the carrying
          capacity. As I get closer, the growth is smaller and
          smaller, showing that population is always approaching but
          never quite reaching the carrying capacity. 
        </p>
      </solution>
    </activity>
  </subsection>
</section>
